<div id="review_3967171285" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3967171285" />
    <a title="Kelli" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6581550-kelli"><img alt="Kelli" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1534220550p2/6581550.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3967171285?book_show_action=true">Apr 30, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kelli" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kelli" href="/user/show/6581550-kelli">Kelli</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer3967171285&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3967171285" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14701193768074896427">I&apos;m shocked by the low rating of this book, but after skimming the reviews I see that those who underrated this magnificent tome simply missed the point or found that complex, and melancholy tales of woe are not for them personally.<br/><br/>This is the story of, spoiler alert, a slave raised by philosophers who doesn&apos;t realize he is a slave at first because of the Classic education he is receiving; he is taught Latin, Greek, and French, as well as schooled in music through the violin. The aim of which wa</span>
  <span id="freeText14701193768074896427" style="display:none">I'm shocked by the low rating of this book, but after skimming the reviews I see that those who underrated this magnificent tome simply missed the point or found that complex, and melancholy tales of woe are not for them personally.<br /><br />This is the story of, spoiler alert, a slave raised by philosophers who doesn't realize he is a slave at first because of the Classic education he is receiving; he is taught Latin, Greek, and French, as well as schooled in music through the violin. The aim of which was originally for the philosophers to prove that Africans are equally as capable of education as Europeans.<br /><br />This is a historical fiction worth reading as you are immersed in the small pox outbreak and American revolution from the vantage point of a slave. We often don't realize that slaves and freemen played a key role in the revolutionary war; therefore, this perspective is not only warranted but highly needed.<br /><br />I recommend this reading to anyone who is historically inclined, enjoys perspective and empathic readings, and desires perspective on current events given the Derek Chauvin trial.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14701193768074896427" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


